. Sigma receptors belong to a unique family of proteins that are different from opioid and N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) phencyclidine receptors (1, 2). They are known to be involved in several disorders of the central nervous system such as schizophrenia, depression, and dementia (3-5). These receptors are classified into two subtypes, sigma-1 and sigma-2. Of the two subtypes, only the sigma-1 receptors are well studied and characterized. It has been demonstrated that [